		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> The State of Lord of the Rings<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.63)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=17'>Neal "Dredlox" Razi</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=17&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> December 17, 2003</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> The State of Lord of the Rings<br />
<br />
As I sit here registering a few domain names, I have been reflecting on the state of Lord of the Rings. As a former top 50 player, owner of DeckTech.net and long time player of Decipher games, I think I have some very valid advice, suggestions and insights for you, the dedicated players and fans of Lord of the Rings TCG.<br />
<br />
What is the state of Lord of the Rings on a tournament level right now?  Actually, while far from dead, it&#39;s at it&#39;s worst state in history.  It pains me to say this, but it is the truth.<br />
<br />
When I started in this game, it was the hottest ticket.  The license was hot, Fellowship had so many strategies, and everyone was excited.  The cross over rate from Star Wars CCG players was very high.<br />
<br />
But now, it&#39;s dropped like a rock. Many of the initial players have dropped, including former number 1 players like Andrew Howard, Craig Berry, and Trevor Bradley. DPC Winners like Gabe Alonso, Steven Lewis, they too have quit. What happened?<br />
<br />
What follows is my take on what is going wrong, and what can be done about it.  Feel free to blast away, that would be fanatastic any input would be welcome over apathy that seems to lately plague our players.<br />
<br />
<br />
<b>Problem One</b>: Too many lackluster sets.<br />
<br />
One dull expansion after another has really hurt this game. It started with Two Towers, dropped to a low with Battle of Helm&#39;s Deep and hasn&#39;t picked up since.<br />
<br />
This is the most critical area of the game. Making the game fun.  As long as new sets are uninteresting, or lack anything other than &quot;put down weapons and skirmish&quot;, this game will continue to decline.  Adding needless complexity to it doesn&#39;t help, it only makes it worse.<br />
<br />
Let&#39;s look at Initiative for a second. Now here&#39;s a stroke of brilliance.  Let&#39;s encourage people to NOT play cards. Sheer genius. See, playing cards, that&#39;s what we call it. Not holding cards.<br />
<br />
Solution: Decipher&#39;s game design team needs an enema.  Lunkhead lackeys like Girard and Snider who got their positions through nepotism need to be cut loose.  Hire some designers with real creativity. Hire real play testers.<br />
<br />
<br />
<b>Problem Two</b>: Horrible marketing.<br />
<br />
I&#39;ve got news for you, if you didn&#39;t know this, Lord of the Rings is one of the hottest properties out right now.  This game should be almost selling itself. Of course, with Decipher&#39;s marketing team, it nearly has to.<br />
<br />
I mean, their idea of strategic brilliance is sneaking into movie theaters and littering the ground with flyers.  What the hell?<br />
<br />
Where are the *real* promotions? Where are the creative tournaments? Where are the business tie ins and contacts?  Nowhere to be found.<br />
<br />
Solution: I&#39;m not saying out of spite that Decipher needs mass firings in their Marketing Dept. Start at the top with Jones. She has absolutely zero creativity and talent, and a personality to match. Hire a marketing director with Charisma, with Intelligence, with Creativity.  There are people out there who can do this.<br />
<br />
Next hit the lower sections. Gaeta, Heuer, Reitzel, these chumps have been on far too long.  Low intelligence almost seems to be a requirement for these posts.  Find some people outside the usual crowd who can come up with ideas. Look, there are players who even could do better, look at someone like Scott Lingrell.  It shouldn&#39;t be that hard.<br />
<br />
<br />
<b>Problem Three</b>: Tournament Structure.<br />
<br />
The tournament structure is in shambles.  Mistakes ranging from poorly run and attended DGMA events (50 people for $5 grand at DragonCon), to the incredible laughing stock of the Decipher Rewards System has absolutely all but ruined the all important tournament structure of this great game.<br />
<br />
Despite what some are preaching over at Decipher, tournament players do run games. They don&#39;t necessarily have to be the champions, but all tournament players, even mediocre ones are what drive sales of this game.  Or what *should* be driving sales, if we could get them back.  They buy the cards, they promote the game, the bring fame to the game. And yet tournaments are at an all time low. While the license is at a high point still.<br />
<br />
Solution: First, the rewards system needs to be placed where it belongs, right in the crapper.  Just take the whole thing and flushimmer down the toilet with the rest of the days excrement. Because that is what it is, just a pile of dung.  It&#39;s insulting that Decipher even seems to be taking it seriously.<br />
<br />
Secondly, the dgma has to be trashed.  It&#39;s proven to be worthless, a big money loser with little return in marketing.  The events are costly, overly competitive in the wrong place, and always fraught with errors.  Now they have lost the one thing they had going for them, cash prizes, replaced with Decipher funny money. I suggest a wild one to Decipher here.<br />
<br />
Contract this out to the DPC.  They(we) are about the only ones with the connections and know how to save this tournament system for you.  Adam Drake, Enrique, Akers, these are the people you need to turn too. I don&#39;t say this out of ego, it&#39;s really about the only hope of something worthwhile.<br />
<br />
<br />
<b>Final Problem</b>: Top Level Mismanagement.<br />
<br />
Warren Holland needs to step down as CEO of Decipher.  I know, it&#39;s his company, but he&#39;s been hurting them for years now.  I&#39;m not saying he shouldn&#39;t continue to own the company, he has his place and his talents.  His main asset is his ability to throw parties for the business elite and keep the contracts rolling in.  For all I can say about his lack of intelligence, ego and stinginess, you&#39;ve got to give him this, he lands the big deals.<br />
<br />
However, he&#39;s more like a Steinbrenner type when it comes to day to day operations.  Everyone who knows anyone at Decipher will tell you, the guy micromanages everything he knows nothing about.  He knows literally *nothing* about what makes a game. Nothing about gamers. Nothing about customer retention. Nothing about effective human resources.<br />
<br />
Solution: Holland needs to step down from the CEO post for the good of his company. Hire someone who can get the job done, and then he needs to stay out of it.  Go sign the contracts and throw the parties, that&#39;s what Holland needs to do.<br />
<br />
<br />
This game should be what it was back in Fellowship: nearly all players of Star Wars CCG should be playing.  This added to multiple cross over Magic players and new fans of the movies.  Those really were the days back in fellowship.  Unfortunately, it hasn&#39;t turned out like that, no it&#39;s now down to the hard core players.  What a shame that a license like this, a great license, one of the greatest fantasy books ever written, academy award winning movies, has a game that is reduced to skulking around back aisles of movie theaters.<br />
<br />
I want this game back.  I propose you take this message right to Warren Holland and the Decipher message boards.  This game can be great, it SHOULD be great again.  All the mistakes lie in Decipher&#39;s half of the court, and could easily be fixed.  It&#39;s up to you, the paying customers, to tell them to do it.  It&#39;s not too late, but something must be done.<br />
<br />
Here&#39;s Warren Hollands email address, please voice your concerns in this.  Tell him, WE WANT OUR GAME BACK! WE WANT IT GREAT AGAIN!  He is the only one who can do this at this point, and you can already smell the cost cutting, corner cutting and mealy mouthed half truths that marks the end of a Decipher game.<br />
<br />
chairman&ceo@decipher.com<br />
<br />
I leave you with this. I want to see 200 people at Origins again. I want it to be 300. I want DPC&#39;s every month. I want prizes to be big, I want promotions, I want a 100,000 players on DT playing this game. Don&#39;t be afraid to speak up if you want this too.<br />
<br />
So sayeth Neal. <br></font><BR><font class="bfont"> <A HREF='/lotr/articles/articles.php?id=5233&view=1&PHPSESSID=...328fedb22570524062aeb1303'>Read the Reviews</a><font class="bfont"> | <A HREF='/lotr/articles/articles.php?PHPSESSID=...328fedb22570524062aeb1303'>Back to List</A></font><p><font class="bfont"> <b>You must be a member to contribute to Decktech.</b>  <p>Please <a href='/lotr/main/join.php?PHPSESSID=...328fedb22570524062aeb1303'> become a registered member</a></font></font></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_09.gif"></td></tr>
